<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920309-0109</DOCNO><DOCID>920309-0109.</DOCID><HL>   Maple Leaf to Close Pork Plant</HL><DATE>03/09/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LABOR T.MLF</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)</NS><RE>CANADA (CN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)</RE><LP>   TORONTO -- Maple Leaf Foods Inc. said it will close itspork processing plant in Kitchener, Ontario, on May 29 andconsolidate all of its Canadian pork operations at a largerfacility in Burlington, Ontario.   About 285 workers at the Kitchener plant will lose theirjobs, while as many as 175 new workers will be hired inBurlington, a company spokesman said. The plant closure won'tresult in a charge to earnings, he said.</LP><TEXT>   The Kitchener plant closing is part of an ongoingrestructuring plan by Maple Leaf, Canada's largest foodprocessor. The Toronto company recently closed a poultryprocessing plant in New Brunswick and sold its Saskatchewanbeef operation.</TEXT></DOC>